1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,370
Pat them on the back for the job they're doing.

2
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:03,570
Give them hope.

3
00:00:03,840 --> 00:00:08,130
Let them know you believe they can succeed, that you have faith in them.

4
00:00:08,320 --> 00:00:10,769
Practice relieving worriers.

5
00:00:11,679 --> 00:00:15,489
Make this little test regularly to keep you on the right track.

6
00:00:15,679 --> 00:00:22,769
Whenever you leave a person, ask yourself, does that person honestly feel better because he has talked with me?

7
00:00:23,199 --> 00:00:25,330
This self-training device works.

8
00:00:25,439 --> 00:00:32,929
Apply it when talking with employees, associates, your family, customers, even with casual acquaintances.

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:37,810
A salesman friend is a real good news broadcaster.

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:44,529
He calls on his customers every month and always makes it a rule to have some good news to pass along.

11
00:00:45,039 --> 00:00:48,850
Examples I met one of your good friends last week.

12
00:00:48,959 --> 00:00:50,769
He said to tell you hello.

13
00:00:51,120 --> 00:00:54,050
Since I was here last, big things have happened.

14
00:00:54,160 --> 00:01:01,729
Over 350,000 new babies were born last month, and more babies means more business for both of us.

15
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:09,170
Usually, we think of bank presidents as overly reserved, unemotional people who never really warm up.

16
00:01:09,279 --> 00:01:11,570
Not so with one bank president.

17
00:01:11,840 --> 00:01:17,009
His favorite way to answer the phone is to say, Good morning, it's a wonderful world.

18
00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:19,009
May I sell you some money?

19
00:01:19,360 --> 00:01:21,090
Improper for a banker?

20
00:01:21,279 --> 00:01:22,610
Some might say so.

21
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:27,410
But let me point out that the banker who uses this greeting is Mills Lane,

22
00:01:27,410 --> 00:01:33,650
Jr., president of the Citizens and Southern Bank, the largest in the entire Southeast.

23
00:01:34,160 --> 00:01:36,209
Good news gets good results.

24
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:37,650
Broadcast it.

25
00:01:38,080 --> 00:01:47,330
The president of a brush manufacturing company I visited recently had this maxim neatly framed on his desk facing the visitor's chair.

26
00:01:47,519 --> 00:01:50,289
Give me a good word or none at all.

27
00:01:50,480 --> 00:01:57,410
I complimented him, saying that I thought the maxim was a clever way to encourage people to be optimistic.

28
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:05,090
He smiled and said, it is an effective reminder, but from where I sit, this is even more important.

29
00:02:05,279 --> 00:02:09,330
He turned the frame around so I could see it from his side of the desk.

30
00:02:09,439 --> 00:02:13,090
It said, give them a good word or none at all.

31
00:02:14,400 --> 00:02:18,769
Broadcasting good news activates you, makes you feel better.

32
00:02:18,959 --> 00:02:22,689
Broadcasting good news makes other people feel better too.

